As Melissa wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/19/2004 at 08:54:57 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>In a math class with 15 students, the instructor assigned probles 
#1 
>through #12. The instructor wants problems #1,#3, and #5 put on the 
>board by three different students. In how many ways can the 
>instructor assign the problems to be put on the board?

Your reasoning is correct.

There is no change in the probability configuration if the 
instructor first allocates question 1, then 3 then 5 to three 
different students.  With 15 students to choose from this can be 
done in P(15,3) =  2730 ways.


>
>[Difficulty]
>What part of the information that my teacher is giving me is 
useless? 
>He is only asking about numbers 1,3 and 5 so I need to work with 15 
>students and those three problems and not be concerned about 1-12 
so 
>that would make it a permutation. But when I went to get help at 
the 
>school math lab one of the helpers thinks that it should be the 
>numbers 1-12 and only putting 3 on the board. But I think that is 
>wrong. So I wanting to make sure.
>
>[Thoughts]
>There are numbers 1,3and 5 to be put on the board. After the 
teacher 
>chooses 1 of the 15 students he only has 14 choices left for the 
next 
>problem and after he chooses the second choice he only has 13 
choices 
>left so...15*14*13= 2730


